## What problem does this solve or what need does it fill?

Currently there is no way to use this pattern for assets (mainly materials) to avoid unnecessary `AssetEvent::Modified` events:
```rust
if material.property != xxx {
    material.property = xxx;
}
```

## What solution would you like?

I'd like for `Assets` to provide entity `Mut`-like API:
```rust
impl<A> Assets<A> {
    #[inline]
    pub fn get_mut(&mut self, id: impl Into<AssetId<A>>) -> Option<AssetMut<A>> {
        let id: AssetId<A> = id.into();
        let result = match id {
            AssetId::Index { index, .. } => self.dense_storage.get_mut(index),
            AssetId::Uuid { uuid } => self.hash_map.get_mut(&uuid),
        };
        Some(AssetMut {
            id,
            asset: result?,
            queued_events: Some(&mut self.queued_events),
        })
    }
}

struct AssetMut<'a, A> {
    id: AssetId<A>,
    asset: &'a mut A,
    queued_events: Option<&'a mut Vec<AssetEvent<A>>>,
}

impl<'a, A> AssetMut<'a, A> {
    pub fn into_inner(mut self) -> &'a mut A {
        self.notify_modified();
        self.asset
    }

    fn notify_modified(&mut self) {
        // notify only once
        if let Some(queued_events) = self.queued_events.take() {
            queued_events.push(AssetEvent::Modified { id: self.id });
        }
    }
}

impl<'a, A> Deref for AssetMut<'a, A> {
    type Target = A;

    fn deref(&self) -> &Self::Target {
        self.asset
    }
}

impl<'a, A> DerefMut for AssetMut<'a, A> {
    fn deref_mut(&mut self) -> &mut Self::Target {
        self.notify_modified();
        self.asset
    }
}
```

This is just a quick snippet from my head, don't know if it even compiles.

## What alternative(s) have you considered?

There are two alternatives (that I know of):
1. store current value in the component and compare to it instead of value in the material
2. get material twice from the assets (`get` for checking value and `get_mut` to change). This is very user-unfriendly because of `Option<T>` result and also double indexing is bad by itself.

## Additional context

This also should sensibly improve performance when devs (like me) are lazy and don't want to create additional components for optimization. 

Just as an example in my project on my machine in debug mode (with `opt-level = 3` for bevy) constantly mutating materials (approx. 50-100 per frame) drops fps from 120- to 90. In release mode it is still 120 but such a huge drop in debug (I wouldn't even think about consequences if not for this drop) still means that a lot of stuff happens under the hood. From what I understood from the sources, `AssetEvent::Modified` leads to the material re-extraction to the render world and re-uploading new values to the GPU.

