bevyengine/bevy#20376.body:
## Bevy version

16.1

## What you did

I constructed the following snippet to test if conditionals that fail validation prevent systems from running:

```rust
use bevy_ecs::prelude::*;
use bevy_ecs::schedule::ScheduleLabel;

#[derive(ScheduleLabel, Debug, Clone, Hash, Eq, PartialEq)]
struct Tick;    

#[derive(Component)]
struct Test;

fn is_true() -> bool {
    true
}

// a run condition that will allow systems to run if the component is present in the world
fn is_present<M: Component>(mode: Single<&M>) -> bool {
    true
}

fn did_i_run() {
    println!("system ran!")
}

fn main() {
    let mut world = World::new();
    let mut schedule = Schedule::new(Tick);

    schedule.add_systems(did_i_run.run_if(is_present::<Test>));
    world.add_schedule(schedule);

    world.run_schedule(Tick);

    world.spawn(Test);
    println!("spawned `Test`");

    world.run_schedule(Tick);
}
```
This works like I expected, the `did_i_run` system doesn't run unless there is a `Test` component in the world.

## What went wrong

I then changed the conditional to
```rust
schedule.add_systems(did_i_run.run_if(is_true.or(is_present::<Test>)));
```
which produces the output
```
> cargo run
system ran!
spawned a Test
system ran!
```

However, when switching the order of the two conditionals, the behavior changes!
```rust
schedule.add_systems(did_i_run.run_if(is_present::<Test>.or(is_true)));
```
Output:
```
> cargo run
spawned a Test
system ran!
```

This means that the position of conditional systems matters when using the `or` combinator: it is not commutative!

bevyengine/bevy#20549.body:
## What problem does this solve or what need does it fill?

As discussed in #15937 and #20518, we could add a trait for the new helper functions to allow them to accept multiple types.

This would make the code look cleaner, because you could use `i32` and `f32` instead of writing `px(10.)`, for example.

## What solution would you like?

Add a trait `AsValNum` that with a method that converts something to a float:

```rust
pub trait ToValNum {
    fn to_val_num(self) -> f32;
}

impl ToValNum for f32 {
    fn to_val_num(self) -> f32 {
        self
    }
}

impl ToValNum for i32 {
    fn to_val_num(self) -> f32 {
        self as f32
    }
}

pub fn px<T: ToValNum>(n: T) -> Val {
    Val::Px(n.to_val_num())
}
```

Open decisions to be made:

- [ ] Final decision: Is this what we want ([although @cart already said yes?](https://github.com/bevyengine/bevy/pull/20518#discussion_r2271599168), just putting this in here again)?
- [ ] For which types do we implement this? All integer types? I think, that would make the most sense

## What alternative(s) have you considered?

Casting to `f32` all the time.

## Additional context

Even though the decision whether we want to implement this seems to have already been made, I'm just moving the design discussion to this issue.

