bevyengine/bevy#20686.body:
## Issue
The `write_buffer_range` function calls `reserve` which, when necessary, allocates a new EMPTY buffer.

When writing a specific range the user probably doesn't expect the rest of the stored values to be zeroed.

## Fix
Include a `copy_reserve` fn which will copy old buffer data into the new buffer and use that function in `write_buffer_range`. 
`CommandEncoder` has `copy_buffer_to_buffer` which may work for this. I'm not sure.

## Disclaimer
I have not actually tested this, I was just perusing the code.

## Source
```rust
pub fn write_buffer_range(
    &mut self,
    device: &RenderDevice,
    render_queue: &RenderQueue,
    range: core::ops::Range<usize>,
) {
    if self.data.is_empty() {
        return;
    }
    let item_size = u64::from(T::min_size()) as usize;
    self.reserve(self.data.len() / item_size, device);
    if let Some(buffer) = &self.buffer {
        let bytes = &self.data[range.start..range.end];
        render_queue.write_buffer(buffer, (range.start * item_size) as u64, bytes);
    }
}
```

```rust
pub fn reserve(&mut self, capacity: usize, device: &RenderDevice) {
    if capacity <= self.capacity && !self.label_changed {
        return;
    }

    self.capacity = capacity;
    let size = u64::from(T::min_size()) as usize * capacity;
    self.buffer = Some(device.create_buffer(&wgpu::BufferDescriptor {
        label: self.label.as_deref(),
        size: size as BufferAddress,
        usage: BufferUsages::COPY_DST | self.buffer_usage,
        mapped_at_creation: false,
    }));
    self.label_changed = false;
}
```

bevyengine/bevy#20802.body:
As of https://github.com/bevyengine/bevy/pull/13693, `bevy_diagnostic` polls CPU info in a background task. This is good! 

Currently it queues a new background task on a more or less fixed interval, and gates the total number of tasks to be half the number of workers in the pool. This approach has several flaws:
+ It relies on information about the workers in the thread pool, which may not be available or consistent on all platforms.
+ It adds redundant load to the pool.
+ It can theoretically result in diagnostics being polled too frequently, resulting in garbage output.
+ It can theoretically deliver polling results out of order.

To avoid these issues, `bevy_diagnostic` should spawn a *single task* which:
1. Waits for the min-update period to pass.
2. Polls cpu the diagnostics.
3. Reschedules itself.

This can be easily implemented as a custom `Future` that always returns `Poll::Pending`, and which transmits results intermittently using an async-channel. The future can re-schedule itself eagerly, and read the CPU data only when enough time has passed since the previous update.

Here is a rough sketch:

```rust
struct DiagnosticJob {
    last_refresh: Option<Instant>,
    data_rx: Sender<SysinfoRefreshData>
}

impl Future for DiagnosticJob {
    type Output = ();

    fn poll(self: Pin<&mut Self>, cx: &mut Context<'_>) -> Poll<()> {
        // Reschedule this task
        cx.waker().wake_by_ref()
        // Determine if it's time to run diagnostics
        let run_diagnotsic = self
            .last_refresh.map(|t| t.elapsed() > MINIMUM_CPU_UPDATE_INTERVAL)
            .unwrap_or(true);
        // Run the diagnostics
        if run_diagnostic {
            let data = get_diagnostic_data();
            self.data_rc.send(data);
            self.last_refresh = Some(Instant::now());
        }
        // Yeild to the executor
        Poll::Pending
    }
```

bevyengine/bevy#20834.body:
The issue appeared with commit afc721e56746f1959afff3bad601b1cf148e8a02 on the main branch.

Since that commit, the colors of a text block built of `TextSpan` nodes is messed up. The `TextColor` of the parent (with `Text`) is correct. But each `TextSpan` child uses the previous `TextColor` component instead of its own, i.e. the first child uses the `TextColor` of the parent, the second child that of the first and so on.

Here's a minimal example if you want to reproduce the issue.

```rust
use bevy::prelude::*;

fn main() {
    let mut app = App::new();
    app.add_plugins(DefaultPlugins)
        .add_systems(Startup, spawn_text)
        .run();
}

fn spawn_text(mut commands: Commands) {
    commands.spawn(Camera2d);

    commands.spawn((
        Text::new("B"),
        TextColor(Srgba::WHITE.into()),
        children![
            (TextSpan::new("e"), TextColor(Srgba::RED.into())),
            (TextSpan::new("v"), TextColor(Srgba::GREEN.into())),
            (TextSpan::new("y"), TextColor(Srgba::BLUE.into()))
        ],
    ));
}
```

bevyengine/bevy#20854.body:
0b47d7685bc33f80d3ab3ca3339630880d5d1ff0 almost fixed the issue described in #20834.

There's still a problem in the corner case where the parent is `Text` (not `Text2d`) and uses an empty string. Then the first child will use the color of the parent instead of its own.  The other children use their own color as expected.

Code sample to reproduce:

```rust
use bevy::prelude::*;

fn main() {
    let mut app = App::new();
