bevyengine/bevy#22842.body:
While looking through `bevy_animations` I noticed that the hashing of `AnimationTargetId`s will produce unwanted collisions.

[This is the relevant code](https://github.com/bevyengine/bevy/blob/f1a954430af1ae123704acbca53da6fa7938b5d8/crates/bevy_animation/src/lib.rs#L1269)

Example collisions:

 - `["bone", "head"]`
 - `["bonehead"]`
 - `["bon", "ehe", "ad"]`

Semantically these are different paths addressing different targets, but they'll all produce the same UUID, because the hashing function just concatenates the names.

This can be fixed by either using a separator or length prefix. I recommend length prefix, because with a separator you'd need to make sure it doesn't appear in names.

Suggested fix:

```rust
    pub fn from_names<'a>(names: impl Iterator<Item = &'a Name>) -> Self {
        let mut blake3 = blake3::Hasher::new();
        blake3.update(ANIMATION_TARGET_NAMESPACE.as_bytes());
        for name in names {
            // added this line
            blake3.update(&(name.len() as u64).to_be_bytes());

            blake3.update(name.as_bytes());
        }
        let hash = blake3.finalize().as_bytes()[0..16].try_into().unwrap();
        Self(*uuid::Builder::from_sha1_bytes(hash).as_uuid())
    }
```

I apologize for not making a pull request. I might make one later :)

