bevyengine/bevy#23273.body:
## Bevy version and features

- Bevy version: 0.19.0-dev
- Commit ID: 162a7080911dc8b782475553fef8888c8d103655
- Feature: default

## Question

The algorithm implementation in `bevy_ecs/src/schedule/graph/tarjan_scc.rs` appears to have a bug, producing unexpected results in tests.

### Test Case

Construct a simple strongly connected graph: `1 -> 2 -> 3 -> 1`
Expected output: `Some([1, 2, 3])` (or any order of these three nodes)

Actual output: `Some([2])`, `Some([1, 3])`, `None`

Test code:
```rust
#[derive(Clone, Copy, Hash, PartialEq, Eq, PartialOrd, Ord)]
pub struct Node(i32);

impl Debug for Node {
    fn fmt(&self, f: &mut core::fmt::Formatter<'_>) -> core::fmt::Result {
        Debug::fmt(&self.0, f)
    }
}

impl GraphNodeId for Node {
    type Adjacent = (Node, Direction);
    type Edge = (Node, Node);
    fn kind(&self) -> &'static str { "" }
}

#[test]
fn a_b_c_a() {
    let mut graph = DiGraph::<Node>::default();
    graph.add_node(Node(1));
    graph.add_node(Node(2));
    graph.add_node(Node(3));
    graph.add_edge(Node(1), Node(2));
    graph.add_edge(Node(2), Node(3));
    graph.add_edge(Node(3), Node(1));
    eprintln!("{:?}", graph);

    let mut scc = new_tarjan_scc(&graph);
    eprintln!("{:?}", &scc.next());
    eprintln!("{:?}", &scc.next());
    eprintln!("{:?}", &scc.next());
}
```

## Possible Cause

Looking at the `visit_once` implementation:

```rust
while let Some(w) = self.nodes[self.graph.to_index(v)].neighbors.next() {
    // If a neighbor hasn't been visited yet...
    if self.nodes[self.graph.to_index(w)].root_index.is_none() {
        // Push the current node and the neighbor back onto the visitation stack.
        // On the next execution of `visit_once`, the neighbor will be visited.
        self.visitation_stack.push((v, v_is_local_root));
        self.visitation_stack.push((w, true));

        return None;
    }

    if self.nodes[self.graph.to_index(w)].root_index
        < self.nodes[self.graph.to_index(v)].root_index
    {
        self.nodes[self.graph.to_index(v)].root_index =
            self.nodes[self.graph.to_index(w)].root_index;
        v_is_local_root = false;
    }
}
```

In a correct algorithm, when visiting node `v` and discovering an unvisited neighbor `w`, we should recursively visit `w` first, and then when backtracking to `v`, update `v`'s `root_index` based on `w`'s result.

However, in this implementation, although we do visit `w` through the loop, when backtracking to `v`, the neighbor `w` has already been consumed from the `neighbors` iterator. This prevents `v`'s `root_index` from being updated with `w`'s final result.

### Step-by-step execution for `a -> b -> c -> a`:

1. Visit `a`: `a.root_index = 1`, discover new neighbor `b`, pause
2. Visit `b`: `b.root_index = 2`, discover new neighbor `c`, pause
3. Visit `c`: `c.root_index = 3`, discover already-visited neighbor `a`, 
   `c.root_index = a.root_index = 1`, `c.is_local_root = false`, push `c` to stack
4. Backtrack to `b`: `b`'s iterator is now empty (already consumed `c`), 
   `b` never gets updated, `b.is_local_root = true`, outputs `Some([b])` ❌

Expected behavior: All three nodes should be in the same SCC.

