rust-lang/rust#47238.body:
This code demonstrates the issue in question:

```rust
#[deprecated(since = "0.1.0")]
mod foo {
    #[test]
    fn stuff() {}
}
```

Attempting to run `cargo test` on this will give an incredibly opaque error message: `use of deprecated item 'foo::__test_reexports'`. I had to resort to grepping rustc's codebase to figure out where this was coming from.

Additionally, there is *no* way to silence this error, other than allowing use of deprecated items for the entire crate. Attempting to put `#[allow(deprecated)]` either on the test itself, or on the deprecated module has no effect.

rust-lang/trait-system-refactor-initiati.body:
Lazy alias relate causes us to no longer (incompletely) infer alias args when we don't normalize aliases to infer vars. That causes this code to (rightfully, IMO) fail:

```rust
trait Foo {
    type Assoc<'a>;
}

fn foo<'a, T: Foo>(_: <T as Foo>::Assoc<'a>) {}

fn test<'a, T: Foo>() {
    let y: fn(<T as Foo>::Assoc<'a>) = foo;
}
```

I'd like to prevent this from being more of an issue, but nothing comes to mind for a good scheme to weaken this inference in the old solver. Ideas?
